SIMPLE: perch
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: perch
<hw>perch</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧rch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>pearch</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[OE. <ets>perche</ets>, F.
<ets>perche</ets>, L. <ets>perca</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>pe`rkh</grk>; cf.
<grk>perkno`s</grk> dark-colored, Skr. <ets>p⟦rsdot⟧⟦cced⟧ni</ets>
spotted, speckled, and E. <ets>freckle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Any fresh-water fish of the genus <gen>Perca</gen> and
of several other allied genera of the family <fam>Percid⟦ae⟧</fam>, as
the common American or yellow perch (<spn>Perca flavescens</spn> syn.
<spn>Perca Americana</spn>), and the European perch (<spn>Perca
fluviatilis</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any one of numerous species of spiny-finned fishes
belonging to the <fam>Percid⟦ae⟧</fam>, <fam>Serranid⟦ae⟧</fam>, and
related families, and resembling, more or less, the true
perches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Black perch</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The black
bass</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The flasher</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>The sea
bass.</cd> -- <col><b>Blue perch</b></col>, <cd>the cunner.</cd> --
<col><b>Gray perch</b></col>, <cd>the fresh-water drum.</cd> --
<col><b>Red perch</b></col>, <cd>the rosefish.</cd> --
<col><b>Red-bellied perch</b></col>, <cd>the long-eared pondfish.</cd>
-- <col><b>Perch pest</b></col>, <cd>a small crustacean, parasitic in
the mouth of the perch.</cd> -- <col><b>Silver perch</b></col>, <cd>the
yellowtail.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Stone perch</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Striped perch</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the pope.</cd> --
<col><b>White perch</b></col>, <cd>the <spn>Roccus Americanus</spn>,
<it>or</it> <spn>Morone Americanus</spn>, a small silvery serranoid
market fish of the Atlantic coast.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Perch
<hw>Perch</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧rch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>perche</ets>, L. <ets>pertica</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
pole; a long staff; a rod; esp., a pole or other support for fowls to
roost on or to rest on; a roost; figuratively, any elevated resting
place or seat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As chauntecleer among his wives all⟦br⟧
Sat on his <qex>perche</qex>, that was in his hall.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not making his high place the lawless <qex>perch</qex>⟦br⟧
Of winged ambitions.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A measure of length containing five and
a half yards; a rod, or pole.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>In land or square
measure: A square rod; the 160th part of an acre.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>In solid measure: A mass 16⟦frac12⟧ feet long, 1 foot in height,
and 1⟦frac12⟧ feet in breadth, or 24⟦frac34⟧ cubic feet (in local use,
from 22 to 25 cubic feet); -- used in measuring stonework.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pole connecting the fore gear and hind gear of a
spring carriage; a reach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Perch
<hw>Perch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Perched</conjf> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧rcht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Perching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>percher</ets>.
See <er>Perch</er> a pole.]</ety> <def>To alight or settle, as a bird;
to sit or roost.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wrens make prey where eagles dare not <qex>perch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Perch
<hw>Perch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To place or to set on,
or as on, a perch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To occupy as a perch.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perchance</ent>⟦br⟧
